# Model Routing: Tri-Model Tiering

The Master selects the appropriate model tier before dispatching each subagent. This rule defines when to use each tier.

## Routing Criteria

### Master tier -- high-reasoning

Use the model defined in `.cursor/models.json` → `master.name` for:

- Initial architectural planning and gestalt creation
- Final review of implementer proof AND verifier report
- Human-in-the-loop decision gates
- Evaluating `ESCALATE` signals that require constraint revision
- Any task where the user explicitly requests deep reasoning

The Master does NOT run as a subagent. It is the orchestrator.

### Sonnet (Mid tier) -- balanced reasoning + speed

Dispatch the implementer subagent with a Sonnet-class model when:

- The previous attempt returned `SURPRISE` with `deviation: high`
- An `ESCALATE` signal requires architectural re-analysis before retry
- The intent touches **more than 5 target files** (cross-cutting refactor)
- The task involves complex type refactoring or migration logic

Use the model defined in `.cursor/models.json` → `mid_tier.name`.

### Flash (Fast tier) -- speed and cost

Dispatch the implementer subagent with `model: fast` when:

- Standard implementation: single-file or few-file changes
- TDD cycles: writing tests, implementing to pass, running tests
- Boilerplate generation, formatting, or mechanical transforms
- The verifier subagent (always runs on `fast`)

This is the **default** for the implementer. Only escalate to Sonnet when the criteria above are met.

## Orchestration Flow

```
Master (Opus) plans + creates handshake
  |
  +--> reads model_routing criteria
  |
  +--> dispatches implementer (Flash or Sonnet based on criteria)
  |       |
  |       +--> returns proof / ESCALATE / SURPRISE to Master
  |
  +--> Master reviews proof
  |
  +--> dispatches verifier (always Fast, readonly)
  |       |
  |       +--> returns pass/fail + summary debt status to Master
  |
  +--> Master issues APPROVE / SUPPRESS / re-dispatches
```

Subagents do NOT nest. The implementer never invokes the verifier. Only the Master dispatches both, sequentially.

## Cost Expectation

Flash absorbs ~80% of execution tokens. Sonnet is used only for high-surprise or cross-cutting work. Opus is reserved for planning and review. Target: maintain or improve the 75-84% cost savings validated in v2 test runs.
